Package com.gtnewhorizon.structurelib.structure

Interface IStructureDefinition<T>

  • Type Parameters:
    T - Type of the context object. Usually this will be the multiblock controller.
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    StructureDefinition
    public interface IStructureDefinition<T>
    This is the structure definition of your multi. You will have one of these for each multi.

    Cache the instances of this class

    You will construct this definition once per multi, either at class load or at first call to your variant of getStructureDefinition(). You can use a ClassValue<IStructureDefinition<?>> if you have a template for subclass. You can also use defer() or its overloads for simpler cases, but it is slightly less performant as it will allocate new objects on each structure check, whereas ClassValue will allocate once and cache it onwards.

    Constructing

    IStructureDefinition is constructed using builder()

    Builder has two main methods:

    • addShape() is a 2d string array describing the layout of structure. You can optionally use `StructureUtility#transpose()` to transpose the array to make the structure look nicer in source code.
    • addElement(). It takes a char identifier (mapped to a char in any of addShape() calls) and a IStructureElement.

    Position A, B and C

    Imagine you stand in front of the controller, with controller facing towards you not rotated or flipped.
    • The "A" position would be the number of blocks on the left side of the controller, not counting controller itself.
    • The "B" position would be the number of blocks on the top side of the controller, not counting controller itself.
    • The "C" position would be the number of blocks between you and controller, not counting controller itself.
